{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509076"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11379"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11379"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.05,0.17,0.53,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94945"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4024"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77941"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1507"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2112"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32527"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94945"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with intermittent vaginal bleeding. She is gravida 2, para 0, with one previous miscarriage at eight weeks gestation two years ago. She is currently in her second pregnancy and was due for her 12-week dating scan next week. She reports passing large clots and tissue yesterday, accompanied by severe cramping pain. The bleeding has since reduced but continues intermittently. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The couple have been trying to conceive for three years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with mild tenderness in the suprapubic region. On speculum examination, the cervical os is closed with no bleeding or tissue visible. Transvaginal ultrasound reveals a thickened endometrium measuring 23 mm with heterogeneous echogenic material measuring 3 x 4 cm within the uterine cavity. No gestational sac is visualised.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Missed miscarriage","Threatened miscarriage","Inevitable miscarriage","Incomplete miscarriage","Complete miscarriage"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincomplete miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features supporting this diagnosis are the history of heavy bleeding with passage of clots and tissue, followed by ongoing intermittent bleeding, and ultrasound findings of a thickened endometrium with heterogeneous material measuring 3 x 4 cm in the uterine cavity. In an incomplete miscarriage, some products of conception have been expelled, but some remain in the uterus. Cervical Os may sometimes be open with incomplete miscarriage - but not always - especially when patients have delayed presentation. Some incomplete miscarriages can be diagnosed weeks later with retained products of conception visualised on ultrasound. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emissed miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with minimal or no bleeding, and ultrasound would show a non-viable intrauterine pregnancy with a gestational sac. This patient has already passed significant tissue and there is no gestational sac visible, making missed miscarriage unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethreatened miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by vaginal bleeding with a closed cervix and a viable intrauterine pregnancy on ultrasound. The lack of a visible viable fetus and gestational sac with the history of passing tissue rule out this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einevitable miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E describes a situation where miscarriage is in progress but no products of conception have yet been passed. The cervix is typically always open or dilated, but expulsion has not occurred. This patient has already passed tissue, making inevitable miscarriage unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when all products of conception have been expelled. The ultrasound shows retained products measuring 3 x 4 cm in the uterus, ruling out a complete miscarriage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement options include expectant management, medical management with misoprostol, or surgical management with vacuum aspiration, depending on clinical factors and patient preference. Follow-up is important to ensure complete expulsion and prevent complications such as infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Incomplete miscarriage is diagnosed by a history of heavy vaginal bleeding with tissue passage plus ultrasound evidence of retained products of conception.","A closed cervical os on examination does not exclude incomplete miscarriage if there is ultrasound evidence of retained products.","Ultrasound findings of heterogeneous material within the uterine cavity without a gestational sac supports incomplete miscarriage."],"references":["BMJ Best Practice. Miscarriage [Internet]. BMJ Publishing Group Ltd 2021; 2020 [Updated 2020; cited 2021 Oct 11]. Available from: https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/666/pdf/666/Miscarriage.pdf","Norwitz ER and Park JS. Overview of the aetiology and evaluation of vaginal bleeding in pregnancy [Internet]. Uptodate; 2021 [Updated 2021; cited 2021 Oct 6]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-the-etiology-and-evaluation-of-vaginal-bleeding-in-pregnancy?search=threatened%20miscarriage\u0026topicRef=5439\u0026source=see_link#H10","Prage S, Micks E and Dalton VK. Pregnancy loss (miscarriage): Clinical presentations, diagnosis, and initial evaluation. In: Uptodate [online]; 2021 [Updated 2021; cited 2021 Oct 6]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/pregnancy-loss-miscarriage-clinical-presentations-diagnosis-and-initial-evaluation"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77941"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11379"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77941"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T15:17:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-26T17:18:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4024"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94945"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"create